<topic id="customize-author-mode-with-sdk">
  <title>Framework Java Extensibility Guide </title>
  <titlealts>
    <navtitle>Java Extensibility Guide</navtitle>
  </titlealts>
  <prolog>
    <metadata>
      <keywords>
        <indexterm>Framework customization<indexterm>Extensions</indexterm></indexterm>
      </keywords>
    </metadata>
  </prolog>
  <body>
    <p product="author editor" id="p_efb_dgk_54b">Advanced users can extend the functionality of custom frameworks and
        <uicontrol>Author</uicontrol> mode. The <xref
        href="https://www.oxygenxml.com/oxygen_sdk.html" format="html" scope="external"><i>Oxygen
          SDK</i></xref> is also available to provide developers the ability to extend the
      functionality of <ph keyref="product"/>.</p>
    <p id="p_ffb_dgk_54b">You can add <xref keyref="glossentry_plugin"><term>extensions</term></xref> to your custom
        <xref keyref="glossentry_framework"><term>framework</term></xref> (document type) by using
      the <uicontrol>Extensions</uicontrol> tab from the <xref
        href="the-document-type-dialog.dita#the-document-type-dialog"><uicontrol>Document
          Type</uicontrol> configuration dialog box</xref>.<note product="author editor" id="note_gfb_dgk_54b">It is
        possible for a <term>plugin</term> to share the same classes with a <term>framework</term>.
        For further details, go to <xref
          href="share-classloader-between-framework-and-plugin.dita#share-classloader-between-framework-and-plugin"
          >How to Share the Classloader Between a Framework and a Plugin</xref>.</note></p>
    <p product="authorEclipse editorEclipse" id="p_hfb_dgk_54b">If you want to customize the Eclipse plugin, you can
      look at the <xref href="https://www.oxygenxml.com/oxygen_sdk/oxygen_eclipse_integration.html"
        format="html" scope="external">Eclipse IDE Integration Sample Project</xref> to see how an
      Eclipse plugin can interact with the <b>Oxygen</b> APIs.</p>
  </body>
